I had a hard time sitting down to write this review, because it’s hard to put into words how much I love Orsos. It is the best cozy neighborhood Italian restaurant in Chicago (which is a very crowded field). Orsos has been a staple gathering place for my family and friends for years. The interior rooms are well decorated and comfortable and the exterior back patio is a great option for a more open dining space in summer or winter. The jalapeño gnocchi and tortellaci dishes are incredible. The Friday night piano player’s initial reluctance to play Billy Joel was a bit off-putting, but she eventually came around. I will be coming back to Orsos for years to come.

I work in the area and I've ordered 4 times. Every single time there was a issue. Ive heard nothing but good things from another co-worker who frequents and I've never had the same experience. The first time i called trying to describe the dish my coworker. The girl on the phone had no clue what i was saying so i googled and called again.  I placed the order which was listed at $10 for lunch. 4pm is lunch right? Asked the girl for my total she said she didn't know. I show up and paid almost $30 for a entree and cannoli.  Got to work after waiting 45mins for my food and it was wrong. However the cannoli was angelic. I then began to weekly buy the cannolis. Each time no price, no pick up time, or coming to pay and phone calls being taken when ive already came 4-5 times checking on a SINGLE cannoli. They were that good. Truly a saving grace.  However ive officially given up on this restaurant. I order 4 very simple items. One, of course, being the cannoli. I showed up an HOUR later to an empty establishment --again extremely time pressed cause i have been waiting an hour-- and it Still was not done.  Of course I'm annoyed but the cannoli is truly worth it, or at least it WAS.  Imagine my horror that after raising the price to $6 that instead of being the yummy treat i nearly pull my hair out for weekly is COMPLETELY different with no warning.  As stated before I weekly come in and order the same thing with the same girl and wasn't warned at all. Instead of one large cannoli for $5 its now $6 for 2 minis that arent even half the size of the original with chocolate all over them and I HATE chocolate. The whole reason i would buy 2-4 cannolis at one time was specifically because they had no chocolate and were so good.  Now that the only thing saving my experience is gone, I no longer will be returning.

I must preface this review with the admission that I only had the catered menu from this restaurant.  I really hope that they take better care when people dine in.  I’ll review three main dishes in this post. The chicken marsala. The sauce was flavorless and watery.  The chicken was dry. Jalapeño Gnocchi. The sauce seemed decent but the gnocchi was the consistency of instant mashed potatoes.  Not gnocchi. And the penne fresco. How do you mess up penne?  Apparently by putting all the cooked pasta in a blender for a few pulses so that the noodles have no discernible shape.  I know catering is a whole different beast than standard restaurant cooking, but for the love of whatever deity you warship, please taste your food before you serve it. I’ve had this place catered before and I thought it was a fluke. Now that the second time is the same consistently poor quality, I know it’s the restaurant. Whether or not the dine-in experience is better doesn’t matter.  I will never be eating there and risking eating this sad attempt at easy Italian dishes.

Walking into orso's is like walking into another century. In the front they have a gorgeous long vintage dark wooden Bar with an extensive selection of liquor.  The main floor dining area is intimate and dimly lit, but has exquisite chandeliers. You can almost picture some of Chicago's old mobsters sitting next to you In the dining area.  There is a gorgeous piano in the back of the first floor dining room, which was not being used, unfortunately, while we were there.  I found it kind of strange, when I asked the employee standing next to the piano when someone would be playing it, he snidely replied I don't know.  We were there on a Thursday night and I hope they have someone playing on the weekends.  Went to an event in the patio, which considering it was December, was closed and well heated. It was wonderfully decorated for the holidays and was a great atmosphere for a party!  There is a separate bar on the patio, and this a great place to have an event.  I'm really looking forward to returning here in warmer weather, and enjoying the patio being open on a nice day.  Unfortunately, we only had pizza and wine that day.   Thin crust cheese, vegetarian, and pepperoni, which was good, not great  I did not get to experience more off of the extensive menu. We will plan a return visit here to try more of the food and soak in the old world decor.
